---
title: Soy Ginger Pork Patties with Roasted Broccoli Salad and Chili Peanut Dressing
description: Why did the pork patties cross the road? To get to the roasted broccoli salad party across the street! Zesty ginger and soy-infused pork patties are seared and served atop a playfully delicious and textural salad of mixed greens, roasted broccoli, crunchy peanuts, and shredded carrots in a piquant chili peanut dressing. It all gets finished with more dressing and scallion greens. Sorry, no more jokes, it’s time to eat!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/soy-ginger-pork-patties-c2c22548.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/soy-ginger-pork-patties-6345a908cb82580fab049905-bdd2a1ae.pdf
time required: 30 minutes
nutrition:
  calories: 830 kcal
  fat: 63 g
  saturated fat: 14 g
  carbohydrates: 31 g
  sugar: 14 g
  protein: 34 g
  fiber: 7 g
  sodium: 1610 mg
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/soy-ginger-pork-patties-6345a908cb82580fab049905
author: HelloFresh
servings: 2
cuisine: Asian
course: main course
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Bring @peanut butter{1.15%ounce} to room temperature. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @broccoli florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Peel and mince @ginger{1%thumb} until you have 1 tsp (2 tsp for 4 servings). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens; mince whites. Roughly chop @peanuts{1/2%ounce}.

Toss broccoli on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of oil, a big pinch of @salt{pinch}, and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a #medium bowl{}, whisk together peanut butter, @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce}, half the @soy sauce{2%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest in the next step), half the @white wine vinegar{5%teaspoon} (all for 4 servings), half the @sesame oil{1%tablespoon} (all for 4), and @sugar{1/4%teaspoon} (1/2 tsp for 4) until combined.

Slowly whisk in @olive oil{3%tablespoon} (6 TBSP for 4) until smooth. Whisk in @warm water{2%teaspoon} (4 tsp for 4) until dressing is smooth. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

In a second medium bowl, gently combine @ground pork{10%ounce}, ginger, scallion whites, @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, remaining soy sauce, @salt{1/2%tsp} (we used 1/2 tsp; 1 tsp for 4 servings), and pepper.

Form into 6 1 1/2-inch meatballs (12 meatballs for 4). TIP: Rub hands with a little oil first to prevent sticking.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add meatballs; gently press down with a #spatula{} to form ½-inch-thick patties (TIP: Depending on the size of your pan, you may need to cook in batches.) Cook until browned and cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} per side.

In a #large bowl{}, combine @mixed greens{4%ounce}, broccoli, peanuts, half the @shredded carrots{4%ounce} (all for 4 servings), and as much dressing as you like (save a spoonful of dressing for serving); toss until thoroughly coated. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

Divide salad between #bowls{}; top with pork patties. Drizzle patties with remaining dressing. Garnish with scallion greens and serve.

> Ground Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.